description:
The '''mod revival''' is a [[subculture]] that started in the United Kingdom in the late 1970s and later spread to other countries (to a lesser degree).

The Mod Revival started with disillusionment with the punk scene when commercialism set in.{{Citation needed|date=April 2024}} It was featured in an article in Sounds music paper in 1976 and had a big following in Reading/London during that time. It gained momentum as an underground movement which was highlighted on London Weekend Show 20 May 1979, prior to the impending release of the film ''Quadrophenia''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2024}}

The late 1970s mod revival was led by the band [[The Jam]], who adopted a stark mod look and mixed the energy of punk with the sound of early 1960s mod influenced bands. It was heavily influenced by the 1979 film ''[[Quadrophenia (film)|Quadrophenia]]''. The mod revival was a conscious effort to hark back to the earlier generation in terms of style and presentation. In the early 1980s in the UK, a mod revival scene influenced by the original mod subculture of the 1960s developed.
